        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Feb 1 1873</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very much obliged to you for your kindness in having sent me your work on Neuralgia; &amp; I have no doubt that I shall find many points in it which will interest me—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>yours truly obliged | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">There is a lightly annotated copy of Chapman’s <hi rend="italic">Neuralgia and kindred diseases of the nervous system</hi> in the Darwin Library–Down (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9061.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">Chapman 1873</ref>; see <hi rend="italic">Marginalia</hi> 1: 165). CD had tried Chapman’s ice treatment in 1865 (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 13, letters to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_885.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Chapman</ref>, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4834.xml" resp="#mjhawkins" cert="high">16 May 1865</ref> and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4854.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">7 June 1865</ref>). Chapman cited CD’s comments on wisdom teeth from <hi rend="italic">Descent</hi> 1: 26–7 in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9061.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">Chapman 1873</ref>, pp. 184–5.</note>
        </div>        
            
